{"type":"message","id":"dfd7d41a","parentId":"03cc05ea","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:22:40.376Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_kn9bmtqruz3u_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 112116\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: a (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me review the current state and what needs to be done:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n2. Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n3. CFI Analysis completed - documented in `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n4. Pending tasks include CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe last pulse had no mutations. I need to take a concrete action that advances the goals.\r\n\r\nLooking at the pending items:\r\n- [ ] CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n- [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n- [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\r\n- [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n- [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\r\n\r\nThe most actionable item seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment. But first, I need to understand what data I have to work with. Let me look at the state files and research documents.\r\n\r\nI should:\r\n1. First observe what's in the current state\r\n2. Take a concrete action - probably creating a script or planning document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist and what the current state looks like. Since I'm stateless, I need to read the files to understand the current state.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals, the most immediate actionable item is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. But I need to create some infrastructure for it. \r\n\r\nA concrete action would be:\r\n- Create a planning document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n- Or create a script/utility that will help with this experiment\r\n- Or update the CFI_RESULTS.md with next steps based on findings\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the notes, the key insight is that 5.7% of invariants have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors). The next step is to compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n\r\nI'll draft a concise experimental blueprint to validate the compression approach. I'll outline the methodology, data sources, and key metrics to measure performance. The document will serve as a clear roadmap for implementing the CFI-weighted compression experiment, ensuring a systematic and focused investigation into the potential improvements over the current frequency-based method.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis is complete with clear findings (5.7% high-CFI invariants are true causal anchors). The logical next concrete step is designing the CFI-weighted compression experiment that compares this approach against the frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate experimental design document for CFI-weighted compression comparison, establishing methodology and success criteria before implementation.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment Design\r\n## Status: PLANNED\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\nCompare CFI-weighted compression against frequency-baseline compression for next-pulse prediction accuracy.\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-based compression because it preserves causal invariants (CFI≥0.7) while aggressively discarding metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0).\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Data Source\r\n- Pulse history: `pulse_*.md` files in root\r\n- CFI scores: Computed from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n- Ground truth: Actual next-pulse content (after gaps)\r\n\r\n### Compression Methods\r\n\r\n#### Method A: Frequency Baseline (current)\r\n- Weight: word_freq / max_freq\r\n- Compress: remove tokens below threshold\r\n- Preserves: common formatting, repeated patterns\r\n\r\n#### Method B: CFI-Weighted (proposed)\r\n- Weight: CFI_score (0-1 scale)\r\n- Compress: remove tokens below CFI threshold\r\n- Preserves: causal invariants, research trajectory\r\n\r\n### Success Metrics\r\n1. **Prediction accuracy**: Token overlap with actual next pulse\r\n2. **Compression ratio**: Tokens removed vs original\r\n3. **Signal preservation**: CFI≥0.7 tokens retained percentage\r\n\r\n### Implementation Steps\r\n1. Parse pulse history → extract token frequencies\r\n2. Map tokens to CFI scores (from invariant analysis)\r\n3. Generate compressed summaries (Method A vs B)\r\n4. Score against actual next-pulse content\r\n5. Compare results\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted will achieve similar compression with higher prediction accuracy, confirming that CFI identifies true causal structure vs noise.\r\n\r\n## Next Actions\r\n- [ ] Build token extraction utility\r\n- [ ] Map tokens to CFI scores\r\n- [ ] Implement compression comparison\r\n- [ ] Run on pulse history\r\n- [ ] Document results\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:21:40\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774365760373}}
